412":"circa 1412","1383":"1383","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","1439":"1439","Tarbock, Lancashire, England":"Tarbock, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Haslington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Haslington, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Haslington, Cheshire, England":"Haslington, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1392–":"about 1392–Deceased","1392–Female":"1392–Deceased","1383–1439":"1383–1439","1412–Male":"1412–Deceased","1418–1458":"1418–1458","1363–Male":"1363–Deceased","1363–Female":"1363–Deceased","about 1392":"about 1392","1458":"1458","1412":"1412","1 January 1418":"1 January 1418","1363":"1363","about 1412":"about 1412","1383":"1383","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","1439":"1439","Tarbock, Lancashire, England":"Tarbock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Haslington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Haslington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Haslington, Cheshire, England":"Haslington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tarbock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Tarbock, formerly in Lancashire, now in Merseyside. The origin of the placename is uncertain, but it may derive from the Old Norse personal name <i>Thor</i>, <i>Thori</i> + Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’, or possibly Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>brōc</i>. Compare   Starbuck   and   Tarbox  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Starbuck","meanings":["English: variant of   Tarbuck   + a prosthetic <i>S-</i>.","History: The Starbucks chain of coffee houses is named after the first mate of the Pequod in Herman Melville's <i>Moby Dick</i>. Melville deliberately used a genuine whaling surname from Nantucket. It was taken to America by Edward Starbuck, a man from Derbyshire, in the 1630s."]},{"name":"Tarbox","meanings":["English (southeastern): variant of   Tarbuck  ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Tarbock was born about 1392, in Tarbock, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Richard Tarbock, was 31 and her mother, Joan, was 31. She had at least 2 sons with Lord Richard Vernon."},"et":{"about 1392–":"umbes 1392–Surnud","1392–Female":"1392–Surnud","1383–1439":"1383–1439","1412–Male":"1412–Surnud","1418–1458":"1418–1458","1363–Male":"1363–Surnud","1363–Female":"1363–Surnud","about 1392":"umbes 1392","1458":"1458","1412":"1412","1 January 1418":"1. jaanuar 1418","1363":"1363","about 1412":"umbes 1412","1383":"1383","1392":"1392","1418":"1418","1439":"1439","Tarbock, Lancashire, England":"Tarbock, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Haslington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Haslington, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Haslington, Cheshire, England":"Haslington, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kin